ampaign song for Clay.\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Henry Clay succession and navigation boxes\n|state     = collapsed\n|list1=\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{US Senator succession box\n| before    = [[John Adair]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| class     = 3\n| alongside = [[Buckner Thruston]]\n| years     = November 19, 1806 \u2013 March 3, 1807\n| after     = [[John Pope (Kentucky politician)|John Pope]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Thomas Worthington (governor)|Thomas Worthington]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of youngest members of the United States Congress|Baby of the U.S. Senate]]|years= December 29, 1806 \u2013 March 4, 1807}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[James Fenner]]}}\n{{US Senator succession box\n| before    = [[Buckner Thruston]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| class     = 2\n| alongside = [[John Pope (Kentucky politician)|John Pope]]\n| years     = January 10, 1810 \u2013 March 3, 1811\n| after     = [[George M. Bibb]]}}\n\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n| before    = [[William T. Barry]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| district  = 5\n| years     = March 4, 1811 \u2013 March 3, 1813\n| after     = [[Samuel Hopkins (congressman)|Samuel Hopkins]]}}\n{{US House succession box\n| before    = [[Samuel McKee (1774)|Samuel McKee]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| district  = 2\n| years     = March 4, 1813 \u2013 January 19, 1814\n| after     = [[Joseph H. Hawkins]]}}\n{{US House succession box\n| before    = [[Joseph H. Hawkins]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| district  = 2\n| years     = October 30, 1815 \u2013 March 3, 1821\n| after     = [[Samuel H. Woodson (Kentucky)|Samuel Woodson]]}}\n{{US House succession box\n| before    = [[John Telemachus Johnson|John Johnson]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| district  = 3\n| years     = March 4, 1823 \u2013 March 3, 1825\n| after     = [[James Clark (Kentucky)|James Clark]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Joseph Bradley Varnum|Joseph Varnum]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]|years= November 4, 1811 \u2013 January 19, 1814}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Langdon Cheves]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Langdon Cheves]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]|years= December 4, 1815 \u2013 October 28, 1820}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after= [[John W. Taylor (politician)|John Taylor]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Philip Pendleton Barbour|Philip Barbour]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]|years= December 1, 1823 \u2013 March 6, 1825}}\n\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[John Quincy Adams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States Secretary of State|U.S. Secretary of State]]|years= March 7, 1825 \u2013 March 3, 1829}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Martin Van Buren]]}}\n\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{US Senator succession box\n| before    = [[John Rowan (Kentucky)|John Rowan]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| class     = 3\n| alongside = [[George M. Bibb]], [[John J. Crittenden]], [[James Turner Morehead (Kentucky)|James T. Morehead]]\n| years     = November 10, 1831 \u2013 March 31, 1842\n| after     = [[John J. Crittenden]]}}\n{{US Senator succession box\n| before    = [[Thomas Metcalfe (Kentucky)|Thomas Metcalfe]]\n| state     = Kentucky\n| class     = 3\n| alongside = [[Joseph R. Underwood]]\n| years     = March 4, 1849 \u2013 June 24, 1852\n| after     = [[David Meriwether (Kentucky)|David Meriwether]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[William Wilkins (American politician)|William Wilkins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on Foreign Relations|U.S. Senate Foreign Relations Committee]]|years= 1834 \u2013 1836}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[James Buchanan]]}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[Silas Wright]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[United States Senate Committee on Finance|U.S. Senate Finance Committee]]|years= 1841}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[George Evans (American politician)|George Evans]]}}\n\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[James Monroe]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] nominee for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]]\u00b9|years= [[1824 United States presidential election|1824]]|alongside = [[John Quincy Adams]], [[William H. Crawford|William Crawford]], [[Andrew Jackson]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Party abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[John Quincy Adams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[National Republican Party|National Republican]] [[List of United States National Democratic/Whig Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]]|years= [[1832 United States presidential election|1832]]}}\n{{s-non|reason=Party abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[William Henry Harrison]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Whig Party (United States)|Whig]] [[List of United States National Democratic/Whig Party presidential tickets|nominee]] for [[President of the United States|U.S. President]]|years= [[1844 United States presidential election|1844]]}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Zachary Taylor]]}}\n\n{{s-hon}}\n{{s-bef|before= [[William Plumer]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of longest-living United States Senators|Most Senior Living U.S. Senator]]<br>{{small|Sitting or former}}|years= December 22, 1850 \u2013 1852}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Elisha Mathewson]]}}\n{{s-new|first}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Persons who have [[lying in state|lain in state or honor]] in the [[United States Capitol rotunda|U.S. Capitol rotunda]]|years= July 1, 1852}}\n{{s-aft|after= [[Abraham Lincoln]]}}\n\n{{s-ref|The [[Democratic-Republican Party]] split in the [[1824 United States presidential election|1824 election]], fielding four separate candidates.}}\n}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Articles related to Henry Clay\n|list1=\n{{US House Speakers}}\n{{United States Senators from Kentucky}}\n{{SenFinanceCommitteeChairs}}\n{{SenForeignRelationsCommitteeChairmen}}\n{{Democratic-Republican Party}}\n{{Whig Party (United States)}}\n{{United States Secretaries of State}}\n{{JQ Adams cabinet}}\n{{Hall of Fame for Great Americans}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 9th\u201332nd [[United States Congress]] |state     = [[Kentucky]]}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/9/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/10}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/11}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/11/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/12}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/13}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/13/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/13/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/14}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/14/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/15}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/16}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/16/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/16/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/17}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/17/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/18}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/19}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/19/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/19/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/19/4}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/20}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/20/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/20/3}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/21}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/22}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/23}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/24}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/25}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/26}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/26/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/27}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/27/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/28}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/29}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/30}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/30/2}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/31}}\n{{USCongRep/KY/32}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Unsuccessful major party pres candidates}}\n{{1840 United States presidential election}}\n{{1844 United States presidential election}}\n{{1848 United States presidential election}}\n{{Lain in State (USA)|state     = collapsed}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clay, Henry}}\n[[Category:Henry Clay|*]]\n[[Category:1777 births]]\n[[Category:1852 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American slave owners]]\n[[Category:Burials in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:College of William & Mary alumni]]\n[[Category:Democratic-Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Democratic-Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Duellists]]\n[[Category:Freedom suits in the United States]]\n[[Category:Great Triumvirate]]\n[[Category:Hall of Fame for Great Americans inductees]]\n[[Category:Henry Clay family]]\n[[Category:John Quincy Adams administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Democratic-Republicans]]\n[[Category:Kentucky lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kentucky National Republicans]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Whigs]]\n[[Category:Members of the American Antiquarian Society]]\n[[Category:Members of the Kentucky House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:National Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:National Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:People from Hanover County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from Kentucky in the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:Second Party System]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Kentucky House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Transylvania University faculty]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1824 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1832 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1840 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1844 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1848 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of State]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Whig Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:Whig Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:American colonization movement]]\n[[Category:American political party founders]]\n[[Category:Clay family]]\n[[Category:Chairmen of the Senate Committee on Foreign Relations]]\n[[Category:White supremacist politicians]]\n", "name_user": "2601:190:c400:115c:d5fc:bec0:55fd:b2da", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Clay"}
{"title_page": "Constantin C. Arion", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Constantin C. Arion\n|image        = 1918 - Constantin C. Arion.jpg\n|caption      =Arion in 1918\n|order        = \n|title        = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Minister of Foreign Affairs of Romania]]\n|term_start   = March 5, 1918\n|term_end     = October 23, 1918\n|predecessor  = [[Alexandru Averescu]]\n|successor    = [[Constantin Coand\u0103]]\n|monarch    = [[Ferdinand of Romania|Ferdinand I]]\n|office2    = [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Minister of Administration and Interior of Romania]]\n|term_start2   = March 28, 1912\n|term_end2     = October 14, 1912\n|predecessor2  = [[Alexandru Marghiloman]]\n|successor2    = [[Take Ionescu]]\n|monarch2    = [[Carol I of Romania]]\n|office3    = [[Ministry of Education, Research, Youth and Sport (Romania)|Minister of Religion and Public Instruction]]\n|term_start3   = July 7, 1900\n|term_end3     = February 13, 1901\n|predecessor3  = [[Constantin Istrati]]\n|successor3    = [[Spiru Haret]]\n|term_start4   = December 29, 1910\n|term_end4     = October 14, 1912\n|predecessor4  = Spiru Haret\n|successor4    = [[Constantin G. Dissescu]]\n|office5    = [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Minister of Agriculture and Royal Domains]]\n|term_start5   = April 5, 1913\n|term_end5     = December 31, 1913\n|predecessor5  = [[Ioan Lahovary]]\n|successor5    = [[Alexandru Constantinescu-Porcu]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1855|06|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bucharest]]\n|death_date =  {{death date and age|1923|06|27|1855|06|18}}\n|death_place = Bucharest\n|spouse       = \n|religion     = \n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         = \n|battles      = \n}}\n\n'''Constantin C. Arion''' (also known as '''Costic\u0103 Arion''';<ref>Boia, p.156</ref><ref name=\"c\u0163\u015fase1OOii\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Constantin \u021aoiu]], [http://www.romlit.ro/fr_ase_1oo_ii \"F\u0103r\u0103 \u0219ase 1OO (II)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103063732/http://www.romlit.ro/fr_ase_1oo_ii |date=2013-11-03 }}, in ''[[Rom\u00e2nia Literar\u0103]]'', Nr. 37/2003</ref> June 18, 1855&nbsp;\u2013 June 27, 1923) was a Romanian politician, affiliated with the [[National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)|National Liberal Party]], the [[Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918)|Conservative Party]] and, after 1918, the [[People's Party (interwar Romania)|People's Party]]. He served two terms as [[Ministry of Education, Research, Youth and Sport (Romania)|Minister of Religion and Public Instruction]], one term as [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Minister of Agriculture]], and another one as [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Interior Minister]] before [[World War I]]. His career peaked in 1918, when he was [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]].\n\nA young lawyer who supported political reform, Arion moved progressively to the [[Right-wing politics|right]], and, ca. 1885, became involved with the political club ''[[Junimea]]''. As a Conservative policymaker and disciple of [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], he rewrote legislation on [[Education in Romania|education reform]] and brought the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] under the control of its high clergy. Like Marghiloman, Arion supported the [[Central Powers]] during most of World War I, a position which seemed to carry most weight during the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|1918 armistice]]. His participation in the Marghiloman government recovered for Romania the region of [[Bessarabia]], but the subsequent return of [[Allies of World War I|Ententist]] forces made him a political suspect. He spent the remainder of his life as a marginal.\n\nIn addition to his presence in political life, Arion was an art patron, university professor, and philanthropist. He was the brother of [[Virgil Arion]], and the father of [[Dinu C. Arion]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nThe Arions were an old [[Wallachia]]n family, first attested in [[Br\u0103ila]] ca. 1696, and integrated into the [[boyar]] aristocracy in the mid-18th century.<ref>Filitti (I), p.9</ref> Its reputation was stained by two members: Constantin Eracle Arion and [[Anton I. Arion]], who had committed massive [[bank fraud]] throughout the early 1870s.<ref>Filitti (I), p.10</ref>\n\nConstantin (born in [[Bucharest]] on June 18, 1855) and Virgil C. Arion were the sons of Appellate Judge Constantin Arion and Sevasti\u021ba, n\u00e9e Url\u0103\u021beanu.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.167</ref> Constantin C. followed in his father's footsteps, graduating in Law from the [[University of Paris]] ([[Doctor of law|Doctorate]] in 1876) and in Political Science from [[Sciences Po]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> Upon his return to Romania, he was made Cabinet Secretary of Foreign Minister [[Vasile Boerescu]], then head of Political Affairs, but left in 1881 to set up legal practice.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/>\n\nTwo years later, he was also employed by the [[University of Bucharest]] Faculty of Law, where he lectured in [[Commercial law|business]] and [[admiralty law]]. He received [[Tenure (academic)|tenure]] in 1913,<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, pp.167, 168</ref> and became editor of the academic journal, ''Revista Critic\u0103 de Drept, Legisla\u021bie \u0219i Jurispruden\u021b\u0103'' (\"Critical Review of Law, Legislation and Jurisprudence\").<ref>Boia, p.163</ref> Virgil had a similar career in law and academia, while a third brother, Scarlat Arion, was a landowner and a Romanian consul in [[Bitola]].<ref>Filitti (II), pp.10\u201311</ref>\n\nC. C. Arion made his debut in politics as a National Liberal, ran in the [[1884 Romanian general election|elections of 1884]], and was elected to the [[Chamber of Deputies of Romania|Assembly of Deputies]] in [[Ilfov County]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> At the time, he was dedicated to the cause of [[representative democracy]], and paid homage to the leadership of [[Liberalism and radicalism in Romania|Romanian radicalism]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/>\n\nBy the mid-1880s, C. C. Arion had become jaded with the ideals of liberalism, and was hostile toward National Liberal [[Prime Minister of Romania|Premier]], [[Ion Br\u0103tianu]]. During 1886, Arion, [[Take Ionescu]] and [[Nicolae Fleva]] were the main \"United Opposition\" agitators who tried to seal a pact with the ''[[Junimea]]'' conservatives, in an effort to topple the National Liberals.<ref>Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.124, 167, 171</ref> He first attended ''Junimea'' club meetings around 1885, when he met and befriended the ''Junimist'' leader, [[Titu Maiorescu]]. The group had past its prime, and, as Maiorescu recorded in his private notes, the sessions attended by Arion were \"rather dull\".<ref>Ornea, pp.91\u201392</ref> The conservative association had been traditionally hostile toward Arion's \"unproductive\" and \"lawyerly\" liberalism. As ''Junimist'' poet-critic [[Mihai Eminescu]] once wrote, the Arion brothers were \"the runts, the intellectual and moral plebs, ... everything basest and most degraded that one can expect to find in the cities of the Romanian nation\".<ref>Ornea, p.225-226</ref>\n\nIn later years, Arion focused on his cultural projects. From 1896, he was president of the national school and public libraries board (''Casa \u015ecoalelor''), where he employed the services of poet [[George Co\u0219buc]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> His legal expertise was demanded in Romania v. Nicolae Georgescu, a ''[[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]]'' for [[honor crime]] in Romania. Arion represented the civil party, Aurelia Stelorian, whom Georgescu had [[Acid throwing|vitriolaged]]; his adversary in court was another famous lawyer, [[Barbu \u0218tef\u0103nescu Delavrancea]].<ref>\"Informa\u021bi\u012d. Atentatul de la \u0219osea\", in ''[[Epoca (Romania)|Epoca]]'', October 2, 1896</ref> Arion and Delavrancea both were celebrity guests at the Bucharest lecture tour of [[Jos\u00e9phin P\u00e9ladan]], the French mystic and novelist (1898).<ref>[[Paul Cernat]], ''Avangarda rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 \u0219i complexul periferiei: primul val'', [[Cartea Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103]], Bucharest, 2007, pp.42\u201343. {{ISBN|978-973-23-1911-6}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative politico===\nReturning to public life as a \"constitutionalist\" conservative, Arion joined ''Junimea'' and served as Minister of Religion and Public Instruction under Premier [[Petre P. Carp]]. His efforts centered on bringing the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] under government control, with the purpose of regulating [[Religious education in Romania|religious education]].<ref>Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, pp.167\u2013168</ref> He oversaw the collecting and publishing historical documents, edited by [[Nicolae Iorga]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\">Filitti (II), p.9</ref>\n\nArion made significant efforts to reverse the policies adopted by [[Spiru Haret]], his National Liberal predecessor. He sacked Haret's favorites and replaced them with ''Junimea'' men, but also introduced legislation which made bureaucratic office incompatible with a teaching position.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.168</ref> The two politicians also differed in matters of church policies. Haret had favored the [[Clerical marriage|married clergy]] over the elitist [[Romanian Synod]], creating a [[wikt:consistory|Consistory]] to represent both sides. Arion reversed that reform, and unwittingly prolonged the conflict well into the 20th century.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Paul Brusanowski, [http://www.revistatransilvania.ro/arhiva/2006/pdf/numarul1/p3-24.pdf \"Biserica \u0219i constitu\u021bionalismul. Cum de s-a putut ajunge la schisma bisericeasc\u0103 din Ardeal din AD 2005?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105080936/http://www.revistatransilvania.ro/arhiva/2006/pdf/numarul1/p3-24.pdf |date=2013-11-05 }}, in ''Transilvania'', Nr. 1/2006, p.14</ref>\n\nAfter the Carp government was dissolved in 1901, Arion returned to academic life. He was still active with the constitutionalist ''Junimists'', worked as editorial adviser for their magazine, ''[[Convorbiri Literare]]'', and, in 1907, followed them into their merger with the [[Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918)|Conservative Party]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\"/> Answering Maiorescu's call, Arion and Delavrancea became political journalists for the main Conservative-''Junimist'' daily, ''[[Epoca (Romania)|Epoca]]''.<ref>Ornea, p.122</ref> By also appointing Arion at ''Convorbiri Literare'', Maiorescu was reaffirming his directorial role. Arion and other new staff members were supposed to undermine the editorial policies of [[Ioan Bogdan (historian)|Ioan Bogdan]] and [[Mihail Dragomirescu]]. Maiorescu dismissed Bogdan's previous management as a triumph of ''m\u00e2rl\u0103nie'' (\"churliness\"), and hoped to reverse the trend.<ref>Ornea, p.129\u2013130</ref>\n\nThis period saw Arion networking and organizing political cabals. He personally intervened to ensure the full-time employment of aspiring jurists, including [[Paul Negulescu]] and his own nephew, Ion Peretz.<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> He met and befriended [[Ion Luca Caragiale]], the ''Junimist'' political satirist. Together with Caragiale and Delavrancea, Arion could be seen dining at the [[Ploie\u0219ti]] restaurant owned by [[Constantin Dobrogeanu-Gherea]].<ref name=\"c\u0163\u015fase1OOii\"/> From 1909, Arion was also active as a philanthropist, serving on the board of [[Elisabeth of Wied|Queen Elisabeth]]'s charitable society, and as honorary president of the Romanian Artists' Society.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\"/>\n\n[[File:Ion Theodorescu-Sion - In redactia revistei.jpg|thumb|320px|Arion (seated at center) and Romanian journalists. [[Cont\u00e9]] drawing by [[Ion Theodorescu-Sion]], ca. 1910]]\nArion was again appointed Public Instruction Minister in 1910, when Carp was named Premier of a Conservative cabinet. He preserved this position after Carp was replaced with Maiorescu, while also serving as head of Internal Affairs and [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Agriculture and Royal Domains]]. It fell on Arion to adopt the [[Land reform in Romania|set of agricultural reforms]] that National Liberal politicians had been postponing ever since the [[1907 Romanian Peasants' Revolt|Peasants' Revolt of 1907]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/> At Public Instruction, he also granted religious and educational privileges to the [[Albanians in Romania|Albanian-Romanian community]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> During the interval, he was elected honorary member of the [[Romanian Academy]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/>\n\nArion's mandate witnessed another outbreak of civic disobedience, this time centered on the public cult of liberal symbols, including images of ''[[Domnitor]]'' [[Alexander John Cuza]]. In order to avoid a showdown between the Conservatives and the National Liberals, Arion agreed to inaugurate the Cuza monument of [[Ia\u0219i]].<ref name=\"amihg\u00eelceav\u0103\">{{in lang|ro}} Andi Mihalache, [http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/local/gilceava-politica-in-jurul-statuii-lui-cuza~ni4kdm \"G\u00eelceav\u0103 politic\u0103 \u00een jurul statuii lui Cuza\"], in ''[[Ziarul de Ia\u0219i]]'', January 24, 2008</ref> At the time, Arion also made public his approval of Romanian [[irredentism]], in respect to [[Bessarabia]] region (taken by the [[Russian Empire]] in 1812). He gave his approval to commemorative marches, and engaged in a publicized row with anti-irredentist Conservatives, such as Mayor [[Dimitrie Greceanu]].<ref name=\"amihg\u00eelceav\u0103\"/>\n\nArion slowly aligned his educational policies with Haret's principles. The \"Arion Law\", adopted by [[Parliament of Romania|Parliament]] in 1912, established clear criteria for the promotion of teachers and academics, ensuring greater [[professionalization]]: teaching positions were granted on the basis of a solid scientific reputation in the respective field of expertise. However, the reform law became especially noted for its loopholes, which allowed senior teachers to reserve academic chairs in advance.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} C\u0103t\u0103lin Boto\u0219ineanu, [http://www.history-cluj.ro/Istorie/anuare/AnuarBaritHistorica2008/13%20Catalin%20B.pdf \"Recrutarea corpului profesoral al universit\u0103\u021bii din Ia\u0219i la \u00eenceputul epocii interbelice. Cazul Petre Andrei\"], in ''Anuarul Institutului de Istorie George Bari\u021biu, Series Historica'', 2008, [[Romanian Academy]], [http://www.history-cluj.ro/ George Bari\u021biu Institute of History], pp.219\u2013223, 233\u2013234</ref>\n\n===World War I and after===\nArion was close to the Conservative leaders Carp and [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], and detested their competitor, [[Nicolae Filipescu]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> He became president of the Bucharest Conservative Club just shortly after the start of [[World War I]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/> Under a National Liberal government, Romania remained a neutral country, a policy that was welcomed by the senior, \"[[Germanophile]]\", Conservatives: Carp, Maiorescu, Marghiloman. They were hotly opposed by another Conservative faction, under Filipescu and [[Take Ionescu]], who demanded engagement on the [[Allies of World War I|Entente side]].<ref>Filitti (II), p.9-10; Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.168-169</ref> As noted by his Conservative colleagues, Arion was \"an optimist\" committed to the Entente, but followed Marghiloman's lead.<ref>Filitti (II), pp.9\u201310</ref>\n\nEventually, in June 1916, the government announced that Romania had [[Treaty of Bucharest (1916)|joined the Entente]], and a trans-party war cabinet was suggested. Arion refused to be part of this project, declaring his sympathy for the [[Central Powers]], and the Conservative Party split in half.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.169</ref> Constantin's brother Virgil and his son, [[Dinu C. Arion|Dinu]] (who was secretary of the Conservative Study Circle) shared his ideas on national politics.<ref>Boia, pp.65, 152\u2013157; Filitti (II), p.11</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[The Romanian Debacle|German advance into southern Romania]], C. C. Arion remained behind enemy lines, in Bucharest; the National Liberal cabinet and its Filipescu Conservative backers had relocated to a temporary home in Ia\u015fi. He still represented Marghiloman's Conservative Club: traveling to [[Foc\u0219ani]], on the front line, he met representatives of the legitimate government and communicated to them the situation in Bucharest.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He frequented the Germanophile circle of [[Raymund Netzhammer]] and [[Marthe Bibesco]], with whom he discussed the idea of granting the [[King of Romania|Romanian throne]] to a [[House of Lorraine|Habsburg-Lorraine]] prince.<ref>Boia, pp.181\u2013182</ref> Virgil Arion was a more radical Germanophile: he agreed to take over as Minister of Public Instruction in the puppet government of [[Lupu Kostaki]], answering to the occupiers.<ref>Boia, p.12, 86, 156\u2013157, 203, 223\u2013224, 360; Filitti (II), p.10</ref>\n\nAfter the shock of the [[October Revolution]] and the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]], Romania yielded to the Central Powers. Marghiloman was appointed Premier, and agreed to sign [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|Romania's withdrawal from the war]] (May 1918). Arion, as Marghiloman's \"second fiddle\"<ref>Boia, p.48</ref> and Foreign Minister up until October 24, was one of the signatories of the Treaty of Bucharest.<ref name=\"ropeace\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=joHTAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Texts of the Roumanian \"Peace\"|author=[[United States Department of State]]|page=113|publisher=Washington Government Printing Office|year=1918}}</ref> He was privately enthusiastic about the turn of events, since he believed that Romania would recover at the same time some of its irredenta, claimed from the [[Russian Republic]], and the territories held by the Central Powers.<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> In this capacity, he traveled to the Russian breakaway region of Bessarabia (or [[Moldavian Democratic Republic]]). Representing Romania, he witnessed the [[Union of Bessarabia with Romania|Bessarabian\u2013Romanian union]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He also made significant efforts to postpone the [[ratification]] of Marghiloman's surrender, allowing Romania to reenter the war on the Central Powers.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/>\n\nWhile affiliated with Margiloman's Conservative Party, Arion also joined the eclectic anti-liberal movement, or [[People's Party (interwar Romania)|People's League]] (the future \"People's Party\"), whose leader was the war hero [[Alexandru Averescu]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [[Duiliu Zamfirescu]], Ioan Adam, [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads//6_2012/092206.pdf ''\u00cen Basarabia'']{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Editura Bibliotecii Bucure\u0219tilor, Bucharest, 2012, pp.25\u201326.  {{ISBN|978-606-8337-29-6}}</ref> His son followed in his footsteps, running on the Conservative list in the [[1918 Romanian general election|1918 elections]].<ref>Boia, p.153; Filitti (II), p.11</ref> In early 1919, Virgil Arion was arrested by the Romanian authorities, on charges of [[collaborationism]]. He was freed in short while, but virtually disappeared from public life until 1930.<ref>Boia, p.153, 356, 358. See also Filitti (II), p.10</ref> Despite his own displays of loyalty, C. C. Arion was also marginalized as a Germanophile by the returning National Liberals.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/>\n\nArion was asked to explain himself before a university inquiry committee, but he never honored the request.<ref>Boia, p.350</ref> He died in Bucharest on June 27, 1923.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He had been the recipient of various orders of merit: a Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]], the [[Order of the Redeemer]], and the [[Order of St. Sava]]; a Grand Officer of the [[Order of Carol I]], the [[Order of the Star of Romania|Star of Romania]], and the [[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honor]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> His son Dinu became a professional historian and lecturer at the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]].<ref>Filitti (II), p.11</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[[Lucian Boia]], ''\"Germanofilii\". Elita intelectual\u0103 rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 \u00een anii Primului R\u0103zboi Mondial'', [[Humanitas publishing house|Humanitas]], Bucharest, 2010.  {{ISBN|978-973-50-2635-6}}\n*{{in lang|ro}} Georgeta Filitti, [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads/Biblioteca_Bucurestilor_2008_nr5%281%29.pdf \"Arion (I)\"], in the Mihail Sadoveanu City Library ''Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor'', Nr. 5/2008, p.&nbsp;9-10; [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads/Biblioteca_Bucurestilor_2008_nr6.pdf \"Arion (II)\"]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor'', Nr. 6/2008, pp.&nbsp;9\u201311\n*{{in lang|ro}} Constantin Gheorghe, Miliana \u0218erbu, [http://www.cultura.mai.gov.ro/biblioteca%20virtuala/editura%20mai/ministri_interne.pdf ''Mini\u0219trii de interne (1862\u20132007). Mic\u0103 enciclopedie''], [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Romanian Ministry of the Interior]], 2007.  {{ISBN|978-973-745-048-7}}\n*[[Z. Ornea]], ''Junimea \u0219i junimismul'', Vol. I, [[Editura Minerva]], Bucharest, 1998.  {{ISBN|973-21-0561-5}}\n\n{{RomanianForeignMinisters}}\n{{RomanianInteriorMinisters}}\n{{First Carp Cabinet}}\n{{Second Carp Cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arion, Constantin C.}}\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Culture]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Education]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Foreign Affairs]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Interior]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (Romania) politicians]]\n[[Category:Junimists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918) politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Party (interwar Romania) politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Romania]]\n[[Category:People from Bucharest]]\n[[Category:Members of the Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Romanian nobility]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Romanian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Finance law scholars]]\n[[Category:University of Bucharest faculty]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:Romanian people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Honorary members of the Romanian Academy]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Crown (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of St. Sava]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Carol I]]\n[[Category:Grand Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:1855 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Constantin C. Arion\n|image        = 1918 - Constantin C. Arion.jpg\n|caption      =Arion in 1918\n|order        = \n|title        = [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Minister of Foreign Affairs of Romania]]\n|term_start   = March 5, 1918\n|term_end     = October 23, 1918\n|predecessor  = [[Alexandru Averescu]]\n|successor    = [[Constantin Coand\u0103]]\n|monarch    = [[Ferdinand of Romania|Ferdinand I]]\n|office2    = [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Minister of Administration and Interior of Romania]]\n|term_start2   = March 28, 1912\n|term_end2     = October 14, 1912\n|predecessor2  = [[Alexandru Marghiloman]]\n|successor2    = [[Take Ionescu]]\n|monarch2    = [[Carol I of Romania]]\n|office3    = [[Ministry of Education, Research, Youth and Sport (Romania)|Minister of Religion and Public Instruction]]\n|term_start3   = July 7, 1900\n|term_end3     = February 13, 1901\n|predecessor3  = [[Constantin Istrati]]\n|successor3    = [[Spiru Haret]]\n|term_start4   = December 29, 1910\n|term_end4     = October 14, 1912\n|predecessor4  = Spiru Haret\n|successor4    = [[Constantin G. Dissescu]]\n|office5    = [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Minister of Agriculture and Royal Domains]]\n|term_start5   = April 5, 1913\n|term_end5     = December 31, 1913\n|predecessor5  = [[Ioan Lahovary]]\n|successor5    = [[Alexandru Constantinescu-Porcu]]\n|birth_date   = {{birth date|1855|06|18}}\n|birth_place  = [[Bucharest]]\n|death_date =  {{death date and age|1923|06|27|1855|06|18}}\n|death_place = Bucharest\n|spouse       = \n|religion     = \n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         = \n|battles      = \n}}\n\n'''Constantin C. Arion''' (also known as '''Costic\u0103 Arion''';<ref>Boia, p.156</ref><ref name=\"c\u0163\u015fase1OOii\">{{in lang|ro}} [[Constantin \u021aoiu]], [http://www.romlit.ro/fr_ase_1oo_ii \"F\u0103r\u0103 \u0219ase 1OO (II)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103063732/http://www.romlit.ro/fr_ase_1oo_ii |date=2013-11-03 }}, in ''[[Rom\u00e2nia Literar\u0103]]'', Nr. 37/2003</ref> June 18, 1855&nbsp;\u2013 June 27, 1923) was a Romanian politician, affiliated with the [[National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)|National Liberal Party]], the [[Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918)|Conservative Party]] and, after 1918, the [[People's Party (interwar Romania)|People's Party]]. He served two terms as [[Ministry of Education, Research, Youth and Sport (Romania)|Minister of Religion and Public Instruction]], one term as [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Minister of Agriculture]], and another one as [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Interior Minister]] before [[World War I]]. His career peaked in 1918, when he was [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Romania)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]].\n\nA young lawyer who supported political reform, Arion moved progressively to the [[Right-wing politics|right]], and, ca. 1885, became involved with the political club ''[[Junimea]]''. As a Conservative policymaker and disciple of [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], he rewrote legislation on [[Education in Romania|education reform]] and brought the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] under the control of its high clergy. Like Marghiloman, Arion supported the [[Central Powers]] during most of World War I, a position which seemed to carry most weight during the [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|1918 armistice]]. His participation in the Marghiloman government recovered for Romania the region of [[Bessarabia]], but the subsequent return of [[Allies of World War I|Ententist]] forces made him a political suspect. He spent the remainder of his life as a marginal.\n\nIn addition to his presence in political life, Arion was an art patron, university professor, and philanthropist. He was the brother of [[Virgil Arion]], and the father of [[Dinu C. Arion]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life and career===\nThe Arions were an old [[Wallachia]]n family, first attested in [[Br\u0103ila]] ca. 1696, and integrated into the [[boyar]] aristocracy in the mid-18th century.<ref>Filitti (I), p.9</ref> Its reputation was stained by two members: Constantin Eracle Arion and [[Anton I. Arion]], who had committed massive [[bank fraud]] throughout the early 1870s.<ref>Filitti (I), p.10</ref>\n\nConstantin (born in [[Bucharest]] on June 18, 1855) and Virgil C. Arion were the sons of Appellate Judge Constantin Arion and Sevasti\u021ba, n\u00e9e Url\u0103\u021beanu.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.167</ref> Constantin C. followed in his father's footsteps, graduating in Law from the [[University of Paris]] ([[Doctor of law|Doctorate]] in 1876) and in Political Science from [[Sciences Po]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> Upon his return to Romania, he was made Cabinet Secretary of Foreign Minister [[Vasile Boerescu]], then head of Political Affairs, but left in 1881 to set up legal practice.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/>\n\nTwo years later, he was also employed by the [[University of Bucharest]] Faculty of Law, where he lectured in [[Commercial law|business]] and [[admiralty law]]. He received [[Tenure (academic)|tenure]] in 1913,<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, pp.167, 168</ref> and became editor of the academic journal, ''Revista Critic\u0103 de Drept, Legisla\u021bie \u0219i Jurispruden\u021b\u0103'' (\"Critical Review of Law, Legislation and Jurisprudence\").<ref>Boia, p.163</ref> Virgil had a similar career in law and academia, while a third brother, Scarlat Arion, was a landowner and a Romanian consul in [[Bitola]].<ref>Filitti (II), pp.10\u201311</ref>\n\nC. C. Arion made his debut in politics as a National Liberal, ran in the [[1884 Romanian general election|elections of 1884]], and was elected to the [[Chamber of Deputies of Romania|Assembly of Deputies]] in [[Ilfov County]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> At the time, he was dedicated to the cause of [[representative democracy]], and paid homage to the leadership of [[Liberalism and radicalism in Romania|Romanian radicalism]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/>\n\nBy the mid-1880s, C. C. Arion had become jaded with the ideals of liberalism, and was hostile toward National Liberal [[Prime Minister of Romania|Premier]], [[Ion Br\u0103tianu]]. During 1886, Arion, [[Take Ionescu]] and [[Nicolae Fleva]] were the main \"United Opposition\" agitators who tried to seal a pact with the ''[[Junimea]]'' conservatives, in an effort to topple the National Liberals.<ref>Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.124, 167, 171</ref> He first attended ''Junimea'' club meetings around 1885, when he met and befriended the ''Junimist'' leader, [[Titu Maiorescu]]. The group had past its prime, and, as Maiorescu recorded in his private notes, the sessions attended by Arion were \"rather dull\".<ref>Ornea, pp.91\u201392</ref> The conservative association had been traditionally hostile toward Arion's \"unproductive\" and \"lawyerly\" liberalism. As ''Junimist'' poet-critic [[Mihai Eminescu]] once wrote, the Arion brothers were \"the runts, the intellectual and moral plebs, ... everything basest and most degraded that one can expect to find in the cities of the Romanian nation\".<ref>Ornea, p.225-226</ref>\n\nIn later years, Arion focused on his cultural projects. From 1896, he was president of the national school and public libraries board (''Casa \u015ecoalelor''), where he employed the services of poet [[George Co\u0219buc]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167\"/> His legal expertise was demanded in Romania v. Nicolae Georgescu, a ''[[cause c\u00e9l\u00e8bre]]'' for [[honor crime]] in Romania. Arion represented the civil party, Aurelia Stelorian, whom Georgescu had [[Acid throwing|vitriolaged]]; his adversary in court was another famous lawyer, [[Barbu \u0218tef\u0103nescu Delavrancea]].<ref>\"Informa\u021bi\u012d. Atentatul de la \u0219osea\", in ''[[Epoca (Romania)|Epoca]]'', October 2, 1896</ref> Arion and Delavrancea both were celebrity guests at the Bucharest lecture tour of [[Jos\u00e9phin P\u00e9ladan]], the French mystic and novelist (1898).<ref>[[Paul Cernat]], ''Avangarda rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 \u0219i complexul periferiei: primul val'', [[Cartea Rom\u00e2neasc\u0103]], Bucharest, 2007, pp.42\u201343. {{ISBN|978-973-23-1911-6}}</ref>\n\n===Conservative politico===\nReturning to public life as a \"constitutionalist\" conservative, Arion joined ''Junimea'' and served as Minister of Religion and Public Instruction under Premier [[Petre P. Carp]]. His efforts centered on bringing the [[Romanian Orthodox Church]] under government control, with the purpose of regulating [[Religious education in Romania|religious education]].<ref>Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, pp.167\u2013168</ref> He oversaw the collecting and publishing historical documents, edited by [[Nicolae Iorga]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\">Filitti (II), p.9</ref>\n\nArion made significant efforts to reverse the policies adopted by [[Spiru Haret]], his National Liberal predecessor. He sacked Haret's favorites and replaced them with ''Junimea'' men, but also introduced legislation which made bureaucratic office incompatible with a teaching position.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.168</ref> The two politicians also differed in matters of church policies. Haret had favored the [[Clerical marriage|married clergy]] over the elitist [[Romanian Synod]], creating a [[wikt:consistory|Consistory]] to represent both sides. Arion reversed that reform, and unwittingly prolonged the conflict well into the 20th century.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} Paul Brusanowski, [http://www.revistatransilvania.ro/arhiva/2006/pdf/numarul1/p3-24.pdf \"Biserica \u0219i constitu\u021bionalismul. Cum de s-a putut ajunge la schisma bisericeasc\u0103 din Ardeal din AD 2005?\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105080936/http://www.revistatransilvania.ro/arhiva/2006/pdf/numarul1/p3-24.pdf |date=2013-11-05 }}, in ''Transilvania'', Nr. 1/2006, p.14</ref>\n\nAfter the Carp government was dissolved in 1901, Arion returned to academic life. He was still active with the constitutionalist ''Junimists'', worked as editorial adviser for their magazine, ''[[Convorbiri Literare]]'', and, in 1907, followed them into their merger with the [[Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918)|Conservative Party]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\"/> Answering Maiorescu's call, Arion and Delavrancea became political journalists for the main Conservative-''Junimist'' daily, ''[[Epoca (Romania)|Epoca]]''.<ref>Ornea, p.122</ref> By also appointing Arion at ''Convorbiri Literare'', Maiorescu was reaffirming his directorial role. Arion and other new staff members were supposed to undermine the editorial policies of [[Ioan Bogdan]] and [[Mihail Dragomirescu]]. Maiorescu dismissed Bogdan's previous management as a triumph of ''m\u00e2rl\u0103nie'' (\"churliness\"), and hoped to reverse the trend.<ref>Ornea, p.129\u2013130</ref>\n\nThis period saw Arion networking and organizing political cabals. He personally intervened to ensure the full-time employment of aspiring jurists, including [[Paul Negulescu]] and his own nephew, Ion Peretz.<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> He met and befriended [[Ion Luca Caragiale]], the ''Junimist'' political satirist. Together with Caragiale and Delavrancea, Arion could be seen dining at the [[Ploie\u0219ti]] restaurant owned by [[Constantin Dobrogeanu-Gherea]].<ref name=\"c\u0163\u015fase1OOii\"/> From 1909, Arion was also active as a philanthropist, serving on the board of [[Elisabeth of Wied|Queen Elisabeth]]'s charitable society, and as honorary president of the Romanian Artists' Society.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219167, 168\"/>\n\n[[File:Ion Theodorescu-Sion - In redactia revistei.jpg|thumb|320px|Arion (seated at center) and Romanian journalists. [[Cont\u00e9]] drawing by [[Ion Theodorescu-Sion]], ca. 1910]]\nArion was again appointed Public Instruction Minister in 1910, when Carp was named Premier of a Conservative cabinet. He preserved this position after Carp was replaced with Maiorescu, while also serving as head of Internal Affairs and [[Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (Romania)|Agriculture and Royal Domains]]. It fell on Arion to adopt the [[Land reform in Romania|set of agricultural reforms]] that National Liberal politicians had been postponing ever since the [[1907 Romanian Peasants' Revolt|Peasants' Revolt of 1907]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/> At Public Instruction, he also granted religious and educational privileges to the [[Albanians in Romania|Albanian-Romanian community]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> During the interval, he was elected honorary member of the [[Romanian Academy]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/>\n\nArion's mandate witnessed another outbreak of civic disobedience, this time centered on the public cult of liberal symbols, including images of ''[[Domnitor]]'' [[Alexander John Cuza]]. In order to avoid a showdown between the Conservatives and the National Liberals, Arion agreed to inaugurate the Cuza monument of [[Ia\u0219i]].<ref name=\"amihg\u00eelceav\u0103\">{{in lang|ro}} Andi Mihalache, [http://www.ziaruldeiasi.ro/local/gilceava-politica-in-jurul-statuii-lui-cuza~ni4kdm \"G\u00eelceav\u0103 politic\u0103 \u00een jurul statuii lui Cuza\"], in ''[[Ziarul de Ia\u0219i]]'', January 24, 2008</ref> At the time, Arion also made public his approval of Romanian [[irredentism]], in respect to [[Bessarabia]] region (taken by the [[Russian Empire]] in 1812). He gave his approval to commemorative marches, and engaged in a publicized row with anti-irredentist Conservatives, such as Mayor [[Dimitrie Greceanu]].<ref name=\"amihg\u00eelceav\u0103\"/>\n\nArion slowly aligned his educational policies with Haret's principles. The \"Arion Law\", adopted by [[Parliament of Romania|Parliament]] in 1912, established clear criteria for the promotion of teachers and academics, ensuring greater [[professionalization]]: teaching positions were granted on the basis of a solid scientific reputation in the respective field of expertise. However, the reform law became especially noted for its loopholes, which allowed senior teachers to reserve academic chairs in advance.<ref>{{in lang|ro}} C\u0103t\u0103lin Boto\u0219ineanu, [http://www.history-cluj.ro/Istorie/anuare/AnuarBaritHistorica2008/13%20Catalin%20B.pdf \"Recrutarea corpului profesoral al universit\u0103\u021bii din Ia\u0219i la \u00eenceputul epocii interbelice. Cazul Petre Andrei\"], in ''Anuarul Institutului de Istorie George Bari\u021biu, Series Historica'', 2008, [[Romanian Academy]], [http://www.history-cluj.ro/ George Bari\u021biu Institute of History], pp.219\u2013223, 233\u2013234</ref>\n\n===World War I and after===\nArion was close to the Conservative leaders Carp and [[Alexandru Marghiloman]], and detested their competitor, [[Nicolae Filipescu]].<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> He became president of the Bucharest Conservative Club just shortly after the start of [[World War I]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219168\"/> Under a National Liberal government, Romania remained a neutral country, a policy that was welcomed by the senior, \"[[Germanophile]]\", Conservatives: Carp, Maiorescu, Marghiloman. They were hotly opposed by another Conservative faction, under Filipescu and [[Take Ionescu]], who demanded engagement on the [[Allies of World War I|Entente side]].<ref>Filitti (II), p.9-10; Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.168-169</ref> As noted by his Conservative colleagues, Arion was \"an optimist\" committed to the Entente, but followed Marghiloman's lead.<ref>Filitti (II), pp.9\u201310</ref>\n\nEventually, in June 1916, the government announced that Romania had [[Treaty of Bucharest (1916)|joined the Entente]], and a trans-party war cabinet was suggested. Arion refused to be part of this project, declaring his sympathy for the [[Central Powers]], and the Conservative Party split in half.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\">Gheorghe & \u0218erbu, p.169</ref> Constantin's brother Virgil and his son, [[Dinu C. Arion|Dinu]] (who was secretary of the Conservative Study Circle) shared his ideas on national politics.<ref>Boia, pp.65, 152\u2013157; Filitti (II), p.11</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[The Romanian Debacle|German advance into southern Romania]], C. C. Arion remained behind enemy lines, in Bucharest; the National Liberal cabinet and its Filipescu Conservative backers had relocated to a temporary home in Ia\u015fi. He still represented Marghiloman's Conservative Club: traveling to [[Foc\u0219ani]], on the front line, he met representatives of the legitimate government and communicated to them the situation in Bucharest.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He frequented the Germanophile circle of [[Raymund Netzhammer]] and [[Marthe Bibesco]], with whom he discussed the idea of granting the [[King of Romania|Romanian throne]] to a [[House of Lorraine|Habsburg-Lorraine]] prince.<ref>Boia, pp.181\u2013182</ref> Virgil Arion was a more radical Germanophile: he agreed to take over as Minister of Public Instruction in the puppet government of [[Lupu Kostaki]], answering to the occupiers.<ref>Boia, p.12, 86, 156\u2013157, 203, 223\u2013224, 360; Filitti (II), p.10</ref>\n\nAfter the shock of the [[October Revolution]] and the [[Treaty of Brest-Litovsk]], Romania yielded to the Central Powers. Marghiloman was appointed Premier, and agreed to sign [[Treaty of Bucharest (1918)|Romania's withdrawal from the war]] (May 1918). Arion, as Marghiloman's \"second fiddle\"<ref>Boia, p.48</ref> and Foreign Minister up until October 24, was one of the signatories of the Treaty of Bucharest.<ref name=\"ropeace\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=joHTAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Texts of the Roumanian \"Peace\"|author=[[United States Department of State]]|page=113|publisher=Washington Government Printing Office|year=1918}}</ref> He was privately enthusiastic about the turn of events, since he believed that Romania would recover at the same time some of its irredenta, claimed from the [[Russian Republic]], and the territories held by the Central Powers.<ref name=\"gfilii9\"/> In this capacity, he traveled to the Russian breakaway region of Bessarabia (or [[Moldavian Democratic Republic]]). Representing Romania, he witnessed the [[Union of Bessarabia with Romania|Bessarabian\u2013Romanian union]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He also made significant efforts to postpone the [[ratification]] of Marghiloman's surrender, allowing Romania to reenter the war on the Central Powers.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/>\n\nWhile affiliated with Margiloman's Conservative Party, Arion also joined the eclectic anti-liberal movement, or [[People's Party (interwar Romania)|People's League]] (the future \"People's Party\"), whose leader was the war hero [[Alexandru Averescu]].<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [[Duiliu Zamfirescu]], Ioan Adam, [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads//6_2012/092206.pdf ''\u00cen Basarabia'']{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, Editura Bibliotecii Bucure\u0219tilor, Bucharest, 2012, pp.25\u201326.  {{ISBN|978-606-8337-29-6}}</ref> His son followed in his footsteps, running on the Conservative list in the [[1918 Romanian general election|1918 elections]].<ref>Boia, p.153; Filitti (II), p.11</ref> In early 1919, Virgil Arion was arrested by the Romanian authorities, on charges of [[collaborationism]]. He was freed in short while, but virtually disappeared from public life until 1930.<ref>Boia, p.153, 356, 358. See also Filitti (II), p.10</ref> Despite his own displays of loyalty, C. C. Arion was also marginalized as a Germanophile by the returning National Liberals.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/>\n\nArion was asked to explain himself before a university inquiry committee, but he never honored the request.<ref>Boia, p.350</ref> He died in Bucharest on June 27, 1923.<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> He had been the recipient of various orders of merit: a Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Crown (Romania)|Order of the Crown]], the [[Order of the Redeemer]], and the [[Order of St. Sava]]; a Grand Officer of the [[Order of Carol I]], the [[Order of the Star of Romania|Star of Romania]], and the [[Legion of Honour|Legion of Honor]].<ref name=\"cgh&m\u0219169\"/> His son Dinu became a professional historian and lecturer at the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]].<ref>Filitti (II), p.11</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n*[[Lucian Boia]], ''\"Germanofilii\". Elita intelectual\u0103 rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 \u00een anii Primului R\u0103zboi Mondial'', [[Humanitas publishing house|Humanitas]], Bucharest, 2010.  {{ISBN|978-973-50-2635-6}}\n*{{in lang|ro}} Georgeta Filitti, [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads/Biblioteca_Bucurestilor_2008_nr5%281%29.pdf \"Arion (I)\"], in the Mihail Sadoveanu City Library ''Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor'', Nr. 5/2008, p.&nbsp;9-10; [http://www.bibliotecametropolitana.ro/Uploads/Biblioteca_Bucurestilor_2008_nr6.pdf \"Arion (II)\"]{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, in ''Biblioteca Bucure\u0219tilor'', Nr. 6/2008, pp.&nbsp;9\u201311\n*{{in lang|ro}} Constantin Gheorghe, Miliana \u0218erbu, [http://www.cultura.mai.gov.ro/biblioteca%20virtuala/editura%20mai/ministri_interne.pdf ''Mini\u0219trii de interne (1862\u20132007). Mic\u0103 enciclopedie''], [[Ministry of Administration and Interior (Romania)|Romanian Ministry of the Interior]], 2007.  {{ISBN|978-973-745-048-7}}\n*[[Z. Ornea]], ''Junimea \u0219i junimismul'', Vol. I, [[Editura Minerva]], Bucharest, 1998.  {{ISBN|973-21-0561-5}}\n\n{{RomanianForeignMinisters}}\n{{RomanianInteriorMinisters}}\n{{First Carp Cabinet}}\n{{Second Carp Cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Arion, Constantin C.}}\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Agriculture]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Culture]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Education]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Foreign Affairs]]\n[[Category:Romanian Ministers of Interior]]\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (Romania) politicians]]\n[[Category:Junimists]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (Romania, 1880\u20131918) politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Party (interwar Romania) politicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Chamber of Deputies (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Senate of Romania]]\n[[Category:People from Bucharest]]\n[[Category:Members of the Romanian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Romanian nobility]]\n[[Category:University of Paris alumni]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Romanian lawyers]]\n[[Category:Romanian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Finance law scholars]]\n[[Category:University of Bucharest faculty]]\n[[Category:Academic journal editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian magazine editors]]\n[[Category:Romanian opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:Romanian people of World War I]]\n[[Category:Honorary members of the Romanian Academy]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of the Crown (Romania)]]\n[[Category:Romanian expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of St. Sava]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Carol I]]\n[[Category:Grand Officiers of the L\u00e9gion d'honneur]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the Order of the Star of Romania]]\n[[Category:1855 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eConservative politico:fixing link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantin_C._Arion"}
{"title_page": "Diocese of Nidaros", "text_new": "{{for|the medieval Catholic archdiocese|Archdiocese of Nidaros}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction = Diocese\n|name         = Nidaros\n|local        = {{lang|no|Nidaros bisped\u00f8mme}}\n|image        = Nidaros cathedral Trondheim 2009 1.JPG\n|caption      = [[Nidaros Cathedral]] in [[Trondheim]]\n|country      = [[Norway]]\n|territory    = [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]] county\n|denomination = [[Church of Norway]]\n|established  = 1068 \n|bishop       = [[Herborg Finnset]]\n|cathedral    = [[Nidaros Cathedral]]\n|deaneries    = 10 ''prosti''\n|parishes     = 134\n|members      = 357,914\n|map          = Dioceses Church of Norway.svg\n|map_caption  = Location of the Diocese of Nidaros\n|website      = [http://www.kirken.no/nidaros kirken.no/nidaros]\n}}\n\n'''Nidaros''' is a [[diocese]] in the [[Lutheran]] [[Church of Norway]]. It covers [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]] county in [[Central Norway]] and its cathedral city is [[Trondheim]], which houses the well-known [[Nidaros Cathedral]].  The diocese is divided into 10 [[deanery|deaneries]] ''(prosti)''.  Since 10 September 2017, the Bishop of Nidaros is [[Herborg Finnset]] who took over from the Bishop [[Tor Singsaas]] who retired.  The [[Preses (Church of Norway)|Bishop Preses]] is also based at the [[Nidaros Cathedral]] and serves as the dean of the [[Nidaros domprosti]] (deanery) in [[Trondheim]]. \n\n==History==\nThe diocese of Nidaros was established in 1068. It originally covered the (modern) counties of [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]], [[Nordland]], [[Troms]], and [[Finnmark]], along with the regions of [[Nordm\u00f8re]] and [[Romsdal]] (in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]] county) and [[H\u00e4rjedalen]] (in [[Sweden]]), and also the northern part of [[\u00d8sterdalen]] ([[Tynset]], [[Tolga, Norway|Tolga]], and [[Os, Hedmark|Os]]). The region of [[Sunnm\u00f8re]] (in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]]) was transferred from [[Diocese of Bj\u00f8rgvin]] to the new [[Archdiocese of Nidaros]] some time after 1152 \u2013 to secure it more income.\n\nThe northern part of \u00d8sterdalen was transferred to the [[Diocese of Oslo]] some time after 1537. The province of [[J\u00e4mtland]] was transferred from [[Diocese of Uppsala]] to Nidaros in 1570. The region of Sunnm\u00f8re was transferred (back) from Nidaros to the Diocese of Bj\u00f8rgvin in 1622. The provinces of J\u00e4mtland and H\u00e4rjedalen were lost to [[Sweden]] in 1645. [[Northern Norway]] was established as a diocese of its own in 1804 (formally first in 1844). The parish of [[Innset, S\u00f8r-Tr\u00f8ndelag|Innset]] was transferred from [[Diocese of Hamar]] to Nidaros in 1966. The regions of Nordm\u00f8re and Romsdal (together with Sunnm\u00f8re from Bj\u00f8rgvin) were established as a diocese of its own ([[Diocese of M\u00f8re]]) in 1983.\n\n==Structure==\n{{see also|List of churches in Tr\u00f8ndelag}}\nThe Diocese of Nidaros is divided into ten [[deanery|deaneries]] ({{lang-no|Prosti}}).  Each one corresponds to several municipalities in the diocese.  Each municipality is further divided into one or more [[parish]]es which each contain one or more congregations. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Deanery (''Prosti'') !! Municipalities\n|-\n| [[Nidaros domprosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Heimdal og By\u00e5sen prosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Strinda prosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Fosen prosti]]||[[Indre Fosen]], [[Osen]], [[\u00d8rland]], [[\u00c5fjord]]\n|-\n| [[Orkdal prosti]]||[[Fr\u00f8ya, Tr\u00f8ndelag|Fr\u00f8ya]], [[Heim, Norway|Heim]], [[Hitra]], [[Orkland]], [[Skaun]]\n|-\n| [[Gauldal prosti]]||[[Holt\u00e5len]], [[Melhus]], [[Midtre Gauldal]], [[Oppdal]], [[Rennebu]], [[R\u00f8ros]]\n|-\n| [[Stj\u00f8rdal prosti]]||[[Malvik]], [[Mer\u00e5ker]], [[Selbu]], [[Stj\u00f8rdal]], [[Tydal]]\n|-\n| [[S\u00f8r-Innherad prosti]]||[[Frosta]], [[Levanger]], [[Verdal]]\n|-\n| [[Nord-Innherad prosti]]||[[Inder\u00f8y]], [[Namdalseid]], [[Sn\u00e5sa]], [[Steinkjer]], [[Verran]]\n|-\n| [[Namdal prosti]]||[[Flatanger]], [[Fosnes]], [[Grong]], [[H\u00f8ylandet]], [[Leka, Norway|Leka]], [[Lierne]], [[Namsos]], [[Namsskogan]], [[N\u00e6r\u00f8y]], [[Overhalla]], [[R\u00f8yrvik]], [[Vikna]]\n|}\n\n==Bishops==\nThe bishops of Nidaros since the [[Protestant Reformation]] when Norway switched from [[Catholicism]] to [[Lutheranism]]:\n{{div col begin}}\n*1546\u20131548 [[Torbj\u00f8rn Bratt]] \n*1549\u20131578 [[Hans Gaas]]  \n*1578\u20131595 [[Hans Mogenss\u00f8n]]  \n*1596\u20131617 [[Isak Gr\u00f8nbech]]  \n*1618\u20131622 [[Anders Arrebo]]  \n*1622\u20131642 [[Peder Skjelderup]]  \n*1643\u20131672 [[Erik Bredal]] \n*1672\u20131672 [[Arnold de Fine]] \n*1673\u20131678 [[Erik Eriksen Pontoppidan d.e.]]  \n*1678\u20131688 [[Christopher Hanssen Schletter]]  \n*1689\u20131731 [[Peder Krog]]  \n*1731\u20131743 [[Eiler Hansen Hagerup]] \n*1743\u20131748 [[Ludvig Harboe]]  \n*1748\u20131758 [[Frederik Nannestad]]  \n*1758\u20131773 [[Johan Ernst Gunnerus]] \n*1773\u20131789 [[Marcus Fredrik Bang]] \n*1788\u20131803 [[Johan Christian Sch\u00f8nheyder]]  \n*1804\u20131842 [[Peder Olivarius Bugge]]  \n*1843\u20131849 [[Hans Riddervold]] \n*1849\u20131860 [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Darre]] \n*1861\u20131883 [[Andreas Grimelund]] \n*1884\u20131892 [[Niels Laache]] \n*1892\u20131905 [[Johannes Skaar|Johannes Nilss\u00f8n Skaar]] \n*1905\u20131909 [[Vilhelm Andreas Wexelsen]] \n*1909\u20131923 [[Peter W. K. B\u00f8ckman Sr.]] \n*1923\u20131928 [[Jens Gran Gleditsch]] \n*1928\u20131942 [[Johan Nicolai St\u00f8ren]] \n*1945\u20131960 [[Arne Fjellbu]]  \n*1960\u20131979 [[Tord Godal]]  \n*1979\u20131991 [[Kristen Kyrre Bremer]] \n*1991\u20132008 [[Finn Wagle]] \n*2008\u20132017 [[Tor Singsaas]]<ref>{{cite news|first1=H\u00e5kon|last1=Jacobsen|last2=Jonassen|first2=Trine H\u00f8klie|title=Her er den nye biskopen in Nidaros|url=http://www.adressa.no/nyheter/trondheim/article1107048.ece|publisher=[[Adressavisen]]|location=Trondheim|accessdate=2008-06-27|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n*2017\u2013present [[Herborg Finnset]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Lutheran dioceses and archdioceses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bishops of Norway}}\n\n{{coord|63.4269|10.3969|region:NO|display=title}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Church of Norway dioceses|Nidaros]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Trondheim]]\n[[Category:1068 establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:11th-century establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Former Catholic dioceses in Sweden]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the medieval Catholic archdiocese|Archdiocese of Nidaros}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n|jurisdiction = Diocese\n|name         = Nidaros\n|local        = {{lang|no|Nidaros bisped\u00f8mme}}\n|image        = Nidaros cathedral Trondheim 2009 1.JPG\n|caption      = [[Nidaros Cathedral]] in [[Trondheim]]\n|country      = [[Norway]]\n|territory    = [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]] county\n|denomination = [[Church of Norway]]\n|established  = 1068 \n|bishop       = [[Herborg Finnset]]\n|cathedral    = [[Nidaros Cathedral]]\n|deaneries    = 10 ''prosti''\n|parishes     = 134\n|members      = 357,914\n|map          = Dioceses Church of Norway.svg\n|map_caption  = Location of the Diocese of Nidaros\n|website      = [http://www.kirken.no/nidaros kirken.no/nidaros]\n}}\n\n'''Nidaros''' is a [[diocese]] in the [[Lutheran]] [[Church of Norway]]. It covers [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]] county in [[Central Norway]] and its cathedral city is [[Trondheim]], which houses the well-known [[Nidaros Cathedral]].  The diocese is divided into 10 [[deanery|deaneries]] ''(prosti)''.  Since 10 September 2017, the Bishop of Nidaros is [[Herborg Finnset]] who took over from the Bishop [[Tor Singsaas]] who retired.  The [[Preses (Church of Norway)|Bishop Preses]] is also based at the [[Nidaros Cathedral]] and serves as the dean of the [[Nidaros domprosti]] (deanery) in [[Trondheim]]. \n\n==History==\nThe diocese of Nidaros was established in 1068. It originally covered the (modern) counties of [[Tr\u00f8ndelag]], [[Nordland]], [[Troms]], and [[Finnmark]], along with the regions of [[Nordm\u00f8re]] and [[Romsdal]] (in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]] county) and [[H\u00e4rjedalen]] (in [[Sweden]]), and also the northern part of [[\u00d8sterdalen]] ([[Tynset]], [[Tolga, Norway|Tolga]], and [[Os, Hedmark|Os]]). The region of [[Sunnm\u00f8re]] (in [[M\u00f8re og Romsdal]]) was transferred from [[Diocese of Bj\u00f8rgvin]] to the new [[Archdiocese of Nidaros]] some time after 1152 \u2013 to secure it more income.\n\nThe northern part of \u00d8sterdalen was transferred to the [[Diocese of Oslo]] some time after 1537. The province of [[J\u00e4mtland]] was transferred from [[Diocese of Uppsala]] to Nidaros in 1570. The region of Sunnm\u00f8re was transferred (back) from Nidaros to the Diocese of Bj\u00f8rgvin in 1622. The provinces of J\u00e4mtland and H\u00e4rjedalen were lost to [[Sweden]] in 1645. [[Northern Norway]] was established as a diocese of its own in 1804 (formally first in 1844). The parish of [[Innset, S\u00f8r-Tr\u00f8ndelag|Innset]] was transferred from [[Diocese of Hamar]] to Nidaros in 1966. The regions of Nordm\u00f8re and Romsdal (together with Sunnm\u00f8re from Bj\u00f8rgvin) were established as a diocese of its own ([[Diocese of M\u00f8re]]) in 1983.\n\n==Structure==\n{{see also|List of churches in Tr\u00f8ndelag}}\nThe Diocese of Nidaros is divided into ten [[deanery|deaneries]] ({{lang-no|Prosti}}).  Each one corresponds to several municipalities in the diocese.  Each municipality is further divided into one or more [[parish]]es which each contain one or more congregations. \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Deanery (''Prosti'') !! Municipalities\n|-\n| [[Nidaros domprosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Heimdal og By\u00e5sen prosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Strinda prosti]]||[[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Fosen prosti]]||[[Indre Fosen]], [[Osen]], [[\u00d8rland]], [[\u00c5fjord]]\n|-\n| [[Orkdal prosti]]||[[Fr\u00f8ya, Tr\u00f8ndelag|Fr\u00f8ya]], [[Heim, Norway|Heim]], [[Hitra]], [[Orkland]], [[Skaun]], [[Snillfjord]]\n|-\n| [[Gauldal prosti]]||[[Holt\u00e5len]], [[Melhus]], [[Midtre Gauldal]], [[Oppdal]], [[Rennebu]], [[R\u00f8ros]]\n|-\n| [[Stj\u00f8rdal prosti]]||[[Malvik]], [[Mer\u00e5ker]], [[Selbu]], [[Stj\u00f8rdal]], [[Tydal]]\n|-\n| [[S\u00f8r-Innherad prosti]]||[[Frosta]], [[Levanger]], [[Verdal]]\n|-\n| [[Nord-Innherad prosti]]||[[Inder\u00f8y]], [[Namdalseid]], [[Sn\u00e5sa]], [[Steinkjer]], [[Verran]]\n|-\n| [[Namdal prosti]]||[[Flatanger]], [[Fosnes]], [[Grong]], [[H\u00f8ylandet]], [[Leka, Norway|Leka]], [[Lierne]], [[Namsos]], [[Namsskogan]], [[N\u00e6r\u00f8y]], [[Overhalla]], [[R\u00f8yrvik]], [[Vikna]]\n|}\n\n==Bishops==\nThe bishops of Nidaros since the [[Protestant Reformation]] when Norway switched from [[Catholicism]] to [[Lutheranism]]:\n{{div col begin}}\n*1546\u20131548 [[Torbj\u00f8rn Bratt]] \n*1549\u20131578 [[Hans Gaas]]  \n*1578\u20131595 [[Hans Mogenss\u00f8n]]  \n*1596\u20131617 [[Isak Gr\u00f8nbech]]  \n*1618\u20131622 [[Anders Arrebo]]  \n*1622\u20131642 [[Peder Skjelderup]]  \n*1643\u20131672 [[Erik Bredal]] \n*1672\u20131672 [[Arnold de Fine]] \n*1673\u20131678 [[Erik Eriksen Pontoppidan d.e.]]  \n*1678\u20131688 [[Christopher Hanssen Schletter]]  \n*1689\u20131731 [[Peder Krog]]  \n*1731\u20131743 [[Eiler Hansen Hagerup]] \n*1743\u20131748 [[Ludvig Harboe]]  \n*1748\u20131758 [[Frederik Nannestad]]  \n*1758\u20131773 [[Johan Ernst Gunnerus]] \n*1773\u20131789 [[Marcus Fredrik Bang]] \n*1788\u20131803 [[Johan Christian Sch\u00f8nheyder]]  \n*1804\u20131842 [[Peder Olivarius Bugge]]  \n*1843\u20131849 [[Hans Riddervold]] \n*1849\u20131860 [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Darre]] \n*1861\u20131883 [[Andreas Grimelund]] \n*1884\u20131892 [[Niels Laache]] \n*1892\u20131905 [[Johannes Skaar|Johannes Nilss\u00f8n Skaar]] \n*1905\u20131909 [[Vilhelm Andreas Wexelsen]] \n*1909\u20131923 [[Peter W. K. B\u00f8ckman Sr.]] \n*1923\u20131928 [[Jens Gran Gleditsch]] \n*1928\u20131942 [[Johan Nicolai St\u00f8ren]] \n*1945\u20131960 [[Arne Fjellbu]]  \n*1960\u20131979 [[Tord Godal]]  \n*1979\u20131991 [[Kristen Kyrre Bremer]] \n*1991\u20132008 [[Finn Wagle]] \n*2008\u20132017 [[Tor Singsaas]]<ref>{{cite news|first1=H\u00e5kon|last1=Jacobsen|last2=Jonassen|first2=Trine H\u00f8klie|title=Her er den nye biskopen in Nidaros|url=http://www.adressa.no/nyheter/trondheim/article1107048.ece|publisher=[[Adressavisen]]|location=Trondheim|accessdate=2008-06-27|language=Norwegian}}</ref>\n*2017\u2013present [[Herborg Finnset]] \n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Lutheran dioceses and archdioceses]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bishops of Norway}}\n\n{{coord|63.4269|10.3969|region:NO|display=title}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Church of Norway dioceses|Nidaros]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Trondheim]]\n[[Category:1068 establishments in Europe]]\n[[Category:11th-century establishments in Norway]]\n[[Category:Former Catholic dioceses in Sweden]]\n", "name_user": "Redriv", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStructure:deleted former Snillfjord municipality", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diocese_of_Nidaros"}
